05705nam a22010695i 9780691218205DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211994nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912182057 a10.1515/97806912182052doi  a(DE-B1597)567566  a(OCoLC)1243310908  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a347.73140922221 aArkes, Hadley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Return of George Sutherland :bRestoring a Jurisprudence of Natural Rights /cHadley Arkes. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b1 halftone  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter I. The Figure in the Carpet -- tCHAPTER II. From the Frontier to the Court: The Shaping of a Mind -- tCHAPTER III. A Jurisprudence of Natural Rights -- tCHAPTER IV. The Heavenly World of the New Deal Lawyers -- tCHAPTER V. The Puzzle of the Commerce Clause -- tCHAPTER VI. Undoing the Discipline of the Constitution: Delegations of Authority and Independent Counsels -- tCHAPTER VII. "In This Vast External Realm . . ." : The Imperatives of Foreign Policy and the Dissolving of the Constitution -- tCHAPTER VIII. Sutherland and the Mysteries of the Law -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book, Hadley Arkes seeks to restore, for a new generation, the jurisprudence of the late Justice of the Supreme Court George Sutherland--a jurisprudence anchored in the understanding of natural rights. The doctrine of natural rights has become controversial in our own time, while Sutherland has been widely maligned and screened from our historical memory. He is remembered today as one of the "four horsemen" who resisted Roosevelt and the New Deal; but we have forgotten his leadership in the cause of voting rights for women. Both liberal and conservative jurists now deride Sutherland, yet both groups continue to draw upon his writings. Liberals look to Sutherland for a jurisprudence that protects "privacy" against the rule of majorities, as in matters concerning abortion or gay rights. Conservatives will appeal to his defense of freedom in the economy. However, both liberals and conservatives deny the premises of natural rights that provided the ground, and coherence, of Sutherland's teaching. Arkes contends that Sutherland can supply what is missing in both conservative and liberal jurisprudence. He argues that if a new generation can look again, with unclouded eyes, at the writings of Sutherland, both liberals and conservatives can be led back to the moral ground of their jurisprudence. This compelling intellectual biography introduces readers to an urbane man, and a steely judge, who has been made a stranger to them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aJudgeszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aNatural law. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh  aAristotle.  aArkes, Hadley.  aBlack, Hugo (Justice).  aBork, Robert.  aCardozo, Benjamin (Justice).  aChaco War.  aCicero.  aCommerce Clause.  aEdwards v. California.  aFederalist papers.  aField, Marshall.  aGibbons v. Ogden.  aGold Clause cases.  aHamilton, Alexander.  aHeller, Joseph.  aHoke v. U.S.  aImportation of slaves.  aJay, William.  aJohnson, Andrew.  aKidd v. Pearson.  aLamar, Lucius (Justice).  aLincoln, Abraham.  aLocke, John.  aMarshall, John (Chief Justice).  aMyers v. U.S.  aNational Recovery Act (NRA).  aNew State Ice Co. v. Liebmann.  aPeckham, Rufus (Justice).  aPrerogative, executive powers.  adelegation of authority.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru